covered: Valid Request scenarios (successful retrieval with default parameters and with various valid query parameters).
Pagination handling scenarios (offset/limit, default limit, large datasets, boundary conditions like offset beyond data, partial inputs).
Error handling scenarios (invalid offset/limit, invalid audit value, invalid parameters, method not allowed).
Edge cases and security scenarios (malformed inputs to test validation and security considerations; SQL injection and XSS attempts).
Data volume and performance/scalability (large data volume, concurrent requests, regression scenarios for boundary conditions).
Integration and dependency scenarios (dependent service unavailable, recovery scenarios).
Empty responses and no data scenarios.
gaps: Caching behavior tests (ETag, Cache-Control headers) are not covered.
Rate limiting/throttling scenarios are not covered.
500 Internal Server Error exposure and handling are not explicitly tested (only 503 service unavailable).
403 Forbidden authorization scenario is not explicitly tested (only 401 unauthorized).
Tests around exact data schema compatibility with screen readers/accessibility is only superficially covered (TC34) and could be deeper.
Some performance-related thresholds (strict timing like <2s for TC19) may require explicit measurable assertions outside basic 200 status.
recommendations: Add explicit tests for caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) and cache validation behavior.
Introduce rate limiting/throttling tests to verify system resilience under rapid successive requests.
Add a test case for 500 Internal Server Error handling to ensure proper server-side error propagation and messaging.
Add a dedicated test to cover 403 Forbidden when authenticated user lacks permissions, in addition to existing 401 scenarios.
Enhance accessibility tests to validate more comprehensive screen-reader compatibility and semantic structure, beyond basic JSON validity.
